<div id="review_1696852078" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1696852078" />
    <a title="Eli" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/63012-eli"><img alt="Eli" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1468263729p2/63012.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1696852078?book_show_action=true">Jun 24, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Eli" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Eli" href="/user/show/63012-eli">Eli</a>
      </span>

          added it


          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780743219563" href="/book/show/656797.The_Skull_Beneath_the_Skin">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/63012-eli?shelf=mystery">mystery</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1696852078" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer767076483746064014">I wouldn&apos;t call most of the characters in this book likeable, except Cordelia (and even her not all the time). But I found them all so well-developed and interesting that just spending time with them became more important to me than learning whodunnit and why. The downside to so many rich characters, of course, is that this book has far less Cordelia Gray than I&apos;d have liked in <em>a Cordelia Gray novel</em>.<br/><br/>And then, of course, there&apos;s the muddle of time periods. It felt to me like an &apos;80s production of</span>
  <span id="freeText767076483746064014" style="display:none">I wouldn't call most of the characters in this book likeable, except Cordelia (and even her not all the time). But I found them all so well-developed and interesting that just spending time with them became more important to me than learning whodunnit and why. The downside to so many rich characters, of course, is that this book has far less Cordelia Gray than I'd have liked in <em>a Cordelia Gray novel</em>.<br /><br />And then, of course, there's the muddle of time periods. It felt to me like an '80s production of a '50s Agatha Christie play, never fully committing to either time period.<br /><br />Still, I always read "just a little more" than I'd planned every time I picked it up and hurried back after I had to put it down.</span>
  <a data-text-id="767076483746064014" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


