<div id="review_2708506883" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2708506883" />
    <a title="Alison" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/89156874-alison"><img alt="Alison" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2708506883?book_show_action=true">Jan 12, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Alison" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Alison" href="/user/show/89156874-alison">Alison</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2708506883" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7205458034975231316">The main character (early 20th century female detective) is sympathetic and interesting, the setting (Byzantine, island castle) is evocative, and the plot sails easily on. Despite this, I found it a bit flat by the end -- possibly because the ending is one of those &apos;there&apos;s no real justice and no one gets a happily ever after&apos;. Although these are fine endings elsewhere, I think that here, the depressive mood gets instilled far too early on, so that the reader is sunk in a morass of gloom by the </span>
  <span id="freeText7205458034975231316" style="display:none">The main character (early 20th century female detective) is sympathetic and interesting, the setting (Byzantine, island castle) is evocative, and the plot sails easily on. Despite this, I found it a bit flat by the end -- possibly because the ending is one of those 'there's no real justice and no one gets a happily ever after'. Although these are fine endings elsewhere, I think that here, the depressive mood gets instilled far too early on, so that the reader is sunk in a morass of gloom by the end.</span>
  <a data-text-id="7205458034975231316" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


